revision.text:
'''Elymas''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɛ|l|ᵻ|m|ə|s}}, also known as '''Bar-Jesus''' ({{lang-grc|Βαριεσοῦ}}, {{lang-arc|Bar-Shuma}}, {{lang-la|Bariesu}}), is a [[Jews|Jew]] in the [[Acts of the Apostles]], chapter 13,<ref>{{bibleverse||Acts|13}}</ref> in the [[New Testament]]. Acts of the Apostles calls him a [[Magi|magus]], which the [[King James Version of the Bible|King James Bible]] here translates as "[[Magician (paranormal)|sorcerer]]". He is represented as opposing the disciple [[Paul the Apostle]], who is called at this point for the first time with his [[Roman name]], and [[Barnabas]] in the city of [[Paphos]] on [[Cyprus]], when [[Sergius Paulus]], the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[Proconsul]], wishes to hear [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] and [[Barnabas]] speak about [[Jesus]]. Because of this opposition, [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] claims that [[God]] had decided to make him temporarily [[Blindness|blind]]. A cloud of darkness immediately begins blocking his sight;<ref>"Immediately mist and darkness fell upon him, and he went about seeking people to lead him by the hand;" {{bibleverse||Acts|13:11}}</ref> after this [[Sergius Paulus]] is converted to [[Christianity]].<ref>"When the proconsul saw what had happened, he believed, for he was amazed at the teaching about the Lord."{{bibleverse||Acts|13:12}}</ref>
Elymas’s intentions for [[Sergius Paulus|Sergius]] are unclear, only that he was desperate to keep him from receiving the word about Jesus. Perhaps he had the proconsul’s ear and was his advisor on matters of faith. This would make sense as [[Sergius Paulus|Sergius]] is obviously learned about Jewish teachings and Elymas is Jewish. The message [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] and [[Barnabas]] bring threatens the false-prophet’s usefulness to the island's most powerful administrator.
Bar-Jesus received the same curse that [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] himself did: temporary blindness.<ref>{{bibleverse||Acts|9:8}}</ref> It is clear from the passage that Bar-Jesus had the ear of the proconsul and was well known throughout the region. He was a self-proclaimed prophet of God<ref>{{bibleverse||Acts|13:6}}</ref> who may have had his own religious agenda.
== Name == Acts 13:8 says "Elymas the Magus (for so his name is translated) opposed them". "Elymas" is possibly derived from the Arabic ''‘alīm'' "learned" or "wise", and may be used to translate ''magos''.<ref>Ernest Haenchen, ''The Acts of the Apostles: A Commentary'', Philadelphia: The Westminister Press, 1971, pg. 398; {{ISBN|0-664-20919-X}}</ref> ''Bar-Jesus'' means "Son of [[Joshua]]" or "Son of [[Jesus]]" in Aramaic.
