{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = Gianni Russo | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birthname = Louis Giovanni Russo | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1943|12|12}} | birth_place = [[Manhattan, New York]], U.S. | death_date = | death_place = | othername = | occupation = Actor, singer | years_active = 1972–present | spouse = }} '''Louis Giovanni''' "'''Gianni'''" '''Russo''' (born December 12, 1943) is an American actor and singer. He is best known for his role as [[Carlo Rizzi (The Godfather)|Carlo Rizzi]] in ''[[The Godfather]]''.<ref name="Jacobs"/>
==Life and career== Russo was born in Manhattan, raised in [[Little Italy, Manhattan|Little Italy]]<ref name="Bio">{{cite web |url=https://www.giannirusso.com/bio/ |title=About Gianni Russo |website=Gianni Russo |access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[Rosebank, Staten Island]]. After reprising the Rizzi character in a brief flashback scene at the end of ''[[The Godfather Part II]]'', Russo went on to act in more than 35 movies, including ''[[Goodnight, My Love]]'' (1972), ''[[Lepke (film)|Lepke]]'' (1975, as [[Albert Anastasia]]), ''[[Laserblast]]'' (1978), ''[[Chances Are (film)|Chances Are]]'' (1989), ''[[The Freshman (1990 film)|The Freshman]]'' (1990), ''[[Side Out]]'' (1990), ''[[Another You]]'' (1991), ''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1993), ''[[Any Given Sunday]]'' (1999) and ''[[Seabiscuit (film)|Seabiscuit]]'' (2003).
Russo claims that he started a fledgling career in [[organized crime]] working as an errand boy and mob associate for [[Frank Costello]]<ref name="Jacobs">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/09/nyregion/his-big-break-the-corleones-killed-him.html | title=His Big Break? The Corleones Killed Him; Godfather's Son-in-Law Is Singing, Selling and Enjoying Life | work=[[The New York Times]] | author-link=Andrew Jacobs (journalist) | first=Andrew | last=Jacobs | date=April 9, 2005 | accessdate=March 26, 2008}}</ref> as an adolescent but later abandoned the dangerous and volatile lifestyle of organized crime.
Over the years since the beginning of his career, he has owned a [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] restaurant called Gianni Russo's State Street (closed in 1988), dated [[Dionne Warwick]] for more than a decade, and successfully defeated 23 federal criminal indictments on a variety of charges stemming from alleged organized crime associations.<ref name="Jacobs"/>
In 1988, he killed a man outside of his Las Vegas club and casino. A member of the Medellín drug cartel was harassing a female patron when he tried to intervene, the man stabbed him with a broken wine bottle. In return, Russo pulled out a gun and killed him.<ref name="Jacobs"/> The case was ruled a [[justifiable homicide]] and Russo was not charged.
Russo is also a singer. In 2004, he released a CD called ''Reflections'' that pays homage to [[Dean Martin]] and [[Frank Sinatra]].<ref name="Bio"/>
Russo owns a wine brand, [[Gianni Russo Wines]] which debuted in 2009. <ref>https://italialiving.com/articles/food-wine/the-intriguing-life-of-gianni-russo-beyond-the-godfather/</ref>
