{{For|the song Mother Maria|Slash (album)}} {{Infobox person | name = Maria Skobtsova | image = NikolayBerdyaev with Maria Skobtzeva.jpg | image_size = 180px | alt = | caption = Maria with [[Nikolai Berdyaev]], 1930 | birth_name = Elizaveta Yurievna Pilenko | birth_date = 20 December 1891 | birth_place = [[Riga]] | death_date = 31 March 1945 (aged 53) | death_place = [[Ravensbrück concentration camp]] | body_discovered = | death_cause = Poison gas | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | residence = Paris | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | other_names = Mother Maria, Mother Mary, Marie Skobtsova | known_for = | education = | alma_mater = | employer = | notable works = | occupation = | years_active = | home_town = Paris, France | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | title = mayor of Anapa | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = Socialist-Revolutionary Party | opponents = | boards = | spouse = | partner = | children = Gaiana, Iuri, Anastasia | awards = Righteous among the Nations
}} {{Infobox saint | honorific_prefix= | name = Mother Maria of Paris | honorific_suffix= Righteous Martyr | image = Елизавета Скобцова.jpg | imagesize = 150px | alt = | caption = Maria Skobtsova | titles = | birth_name = Elizaveta Pilenko | birth_date = 20 December 1891 | birth_place = [[Riga]] | residence = 77, Rue de Lourmel, [[Grenelle]], [[15th arrondissement of Paris]] | death_date = 31 March 1945 | death_place = [[Ravensbrück concentration camp]] | venerated_in = [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] | canonized_date = 1 May 2004<ref>http://www.ukrainian-orthodoxy.org/saints/saints_new/martyr.htm</ref> | canonized_place = [[Istanbul]] | canonized_by = the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]]. | feast_day = 20 July<ref>https://oca.org/saints/lives/2008/07/20/108892-righteous-martyr-maria-skobtsova</ref> | influenced = | major_works = }} '''Maria Skobtsova''' (20 [8 [[Old Calendar]]] December 1891 in Riga – 31 March 1945 in [[Ravensbrück concentration camp]], Germany), known as ''Mother Maria'' ({{lang-ru|Мать Мария}}), Saint Mary (or Mother Maria) of Paris, born ''Elizaveta Yurievna Pilenko'' (Елизавета Юрьевна Пиленко), ''Kuzmina-Karavayeva'' (Кузьмина-Караваева) by her first marriage, ''Skobtsova'' (Скобцова) by her second marriage, was a [[Russian nobility|Russian noblewoman]], [[poet]], [[nun]], and member of the [[French Resistance]] during [[World War II]]. She has been [[canonization|canonized]] a [[saint]] in the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]].
==Life== [[File:Maria Skobtsova Commemorative Plaque (Saint Petersburg) 19Jun10.JPG|thumb|left|220px|Maria Skobtsova Commemorative Plaque in Saint Petersburg]] Born to an aristocratic family in 1891 in [[Riga]], [[Latvia]], then part of the [[Russian Empire]]. She was given the name Elizaveta Pilenko.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Koulomzin |first1= Sophie |year= |title= Mother Mary |journal= Upbeat |volume= 12 |issue= 1 |pages= |url= http://www.orthodoxed.org/files/Mother_Mary.pdf |doi= }}</ref> Her father died when she was a teenager, and she embraced [[atheism]]. In 1906 her mother moved the family to [[St. Petersburg]], where she became involved in radical intellectual circles. In 1910 she married a [[Bolsheviks|Bolshevik]] by the name of [[Dmitriy Kuz'min-Karavaev]]. During this period of her life she was actively involved in literary circles and wrote much poetry. Her first book, Scythian Shards (Скифские черепки), was a collection of poetry from this period. By 1913 her marriage to Dimitriy had ended and the latter subsequently became Eastern Orthodox.
Through a look at the humanity of [[Christ]] — "He also died. He sweated blood. They struck his face" — she began to be drawn back into Christianity. She moved—now with her daughter, Gaiana—to the south of Russia where her religious devotion increased.
Furious at [[Leon Trotsky]] for closing the [[Socialist-Revolutionary Party]] Congress, she planned his [[assassination]], but was dissuaded by colleagues, who sent her to [[Anapa]].<ref>{{cite book |last1= Paldiel |first1= Mordechai |authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |others= |title= Saving the Jews : amazing stories of men and women who defied the "Final Solution |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=gRdUvDLC3pgC&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=%22elizabeth+pilenko%22+saint&source=bl&ots=P-_545ZU-R&sig=uz-S1wOh1buAmHDkKZ_jde5lm28&hl=en&ei=KMCBS5HLEtWwngfk8KGdBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CBEQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=&f=false |year= 2000 |publisher= Scribner |location= Rockville, Maryland |isbn= 978-1-887563-55-0 |oclc= 231868099 |page= 211 |quote= }}</ref> In 1918, after the [[Bolshevik Revolution]], she was elected deputy mayor of Anapa in Southern Russia. When the [[anti-communist]] [[White Army]] took control of Anapa, the mayor fled and she became mayor of the town. The White Army put her on trial for being a Bolshevik. However, the judge was a former teacher of hers, Daniel Skobtsov, and she was acquitted. Soon the two fell in love and were married.
Soon, the political tide was turning again. In order to avoid danger, Elizaveta, Daniel, Gaiana, and Elizaveta's mother Sophia fled the country. Elizaveta was pregnant with her second child. They traveled first to [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] (where her son Yuri was born) and then to [[Yugoslavia]] (where her daughter Anastasia was born). Finally they arrived in [[Paris]] in 1923. Soon Elizaveta was dedicating herself to theological studies and social work.
In 1926, Anastasia died of influenza. Gaiana was sent away to [[Belgium]] to boarding school. Soon, Daniel and Elizaveta's marriage was falling apart. Yuri ended up living with Daniel, and Elizaveta moved into central Paris to work more directly with those who were most in need.
Her bishop encouraged her to take vows as a nun, something she did only with the assurance that she would not have to live in a monastery, secluded from the world. In 1932, with Daniel Skobtov's permission, an ecclesiastical divorce was granted and she took monastic vows. In religion she took the name Maria. Her confessor was Father [[Sergei Bulgakov]]. Later, Fr. [[Dmitri Klepinin]] would be sent to be the chaplain of the house.
Mother Maria made a rented house in Paris her "convent". It was a place with an open door for refugees, the needy and the lonely. It also soon became a center for intellectual and theological discussion. In Mother Maria these two elements—service to the poor and theology—went hand-in-hand.
==Death== After the [[Fall of France]] in 1940, Jews began approaching the house asking for [[baptism]]al certificates, which Father Dimitri would provide them. Many Jews came to stay with them. They provided shelter and helped many to flee the country. Eventually the house was closed down. Mother Maria, Fr. Dimitri, Yuri and Sophia were all arrested by the [[Gestapo]]. Fr. Dimitri and Yuri both died at the [[Dora concentration camp]].
Mother Maria was sent to the [[Ravensbrück concentration camp]]. On [[Holy Saturday]], 1945, she failed a selection and was sent to the [[Gas Chamber]].
==Canonization== Mother Maria was [[Canonization|glorified]] (canonized a [[saint]]) by act of the [[Synod|Holy Synod]] of the [[Ecumenical Patriarchate]] on 16 January 2004. The glorification of Mother Maria, together with Fr. Dimitri, Yuri, and Ilya Fondaminsky took place at the Cathedral of Saint Alexander Nevsky in Paris on 1 and 2 May 2004. Their feast day is 20 July. <ref>http://www.ukrainian-orthodoxy.org/saints/saints_new/martyr.htm</ref>
==Legacy== Her life is dramatized in a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] film starring [[Lyudmila Kasatkina]].
According to [[Metropolitan Anthony (Bloom) of Sourozh]]: "Mother Maria is a saint of our day and for our day; a woman of flesh and blood possessed by the love of God, who stood face to face with the problems of this century."
==Example of poetry== In July, 1942, when the order requiring Jews to wear the [[yellow badge|yellow star]] was published, she wrote a poem entitled "Israel":
:Two triangles, a star, :The shield of King David, our forefather. :This is election, not offense. :The great path and not an evil. :Once more in a term fulfilled, :Once more roars the trumpet of the end; :And the fate of a great people :Once more is by the prophet proclaimed. :Thou art persecuted again, O Israel, :But what can human malice mean to thee, :who have heard the thunder from Sinai?
