[[File:Robert C. Seacord.jpg|thumbnail|150px|right|Robert C. Seacord]]
'''Robert C. Seacord''' (born June 5, 1963) is an American [[computer security]] specialist and [[writer]].  He is the author of books on [[computer security]], [[legacy system]] modernization, and [[component-based]] software engineering.

== Education ==
Seacord earned a [[Bachelor's degree]] in [[computer science]] from [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] in December 1983. He has also completed graduate-level courses at [[Carnegie Mellon University|Carnegie-Mellon University]] in software design, creation and maintenance; user interfaces; software project management; formal methods; human factors; operating systems; and entrepreneurship.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}

== Career ==
Seacord began programming professionally for [[IBM]] in 1984, working in processor development, then communications and operating system software, and software engineering. He led the Secure Coding Initiative in the  CERT Division’s [[Software Engineering Institute]] (SEI) in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania until 1991.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.us-cert.gov/bsi/about-us/authors/robert-c-seacord|title=Robert C. Seacord {{!}} US-CERT|website=www.us-cert.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> He also has worked at the [[X Consortium]] in Cambridge, Massachusetts, where he developed and maintained code for the Common Desktop Environment and the X Window System. He returned to SEI in 1996, working on component-based software engineering.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.informit.com/articles/article.aspx?p=1315064|title=Robert Seacord on the CERT C Secure Coding Standard|last=Chisnall|first=David|last2=Seacord|first2=Robert C.|date=2008-12-15}}</ref>

Seacord joined [[NCC Group]] in 2015<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nccgroup.trust/us/about-us/newsroom-and-events/press-releases/2015/november/renowned-secure-coding-expert-and-author-joins-ncc-groups-us-team/|title=Renowned secure coding expert and author joins NCC Group’s US team|last=|first=|date=4 November 2015|website=www.nccgroup.trust|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref> and is currently a Technical Director. Seacord was an [[adjunct professor]] in the [[Carnegie Mellon School of Computer Science]] and in the [[Information Networking Institute]].<ref name=":0" /> He was also a part-time faculty member at the [[University of Pittsburgh]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}. In early 2018, Seacord tweeted that "As a Carnegie Mellon professor, I didn’t spend a lot of time catering to struggling students. I think this diverts resources from those who are going to succeed and make a difference." The tweet was quickly deleted but was later reported about in [[The Tartan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thetartan.org/2018/2/5/news/tweets|title=CMU students and professors react to controversial tweet|last=Green|first=Lydia|date=February 5, 2018|work=The Tartan|access-date=7 February 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|website=}}</ref>

Seacord is on the Advisory Board for the [[Linux Foundation]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coreinfrastructure.org/advisory-board/|title=Advisory Board}}</ref> and a technical expert for the ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG14 international standardization working group for the [[C (programming language)|C programming language]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://resources.sei.cmu.edu/asset_files/certresearchreport/2009_013_001_54244.pdf#page=74|title=CERT Research Annual Report|date=2009|website=|page=76|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref>

